<ce:para>Quantum chemical calculations with density functional theory (DFT) have been very valuable for estimating the thermodynamics of metal hydrides for hydrogen storage. The kinetics of hydrogenation/dehydrogenation of metal hydrides is just as critical as thermodynamic aspects of hydrogen storage, yet kinetics of solid phase reactions is very difficult to study from first principles. We have studied surface reactions on three metal hydrides as a first step toward understanding kinetic poisoning. We present DFT calculations for the adsorption and dissociation energetics of H <inf>2</inf>O, O <inf>2</inf>, and H <inf>2</inf> on the surfaces of LiH, NaH and KH. We find that the LiH surface is more easily contaminated by oxygen than NaH and KH surfaces. Adsorption calculations indicate that H <inf>2</inf>O initially physisorbs on the three metal hydride surfaces at low coverage. Dissociative chemisorption of O <inf>2</inf> and H <inf>2</inf>O on the surface of LiH both leads to the formation of surface LiOH. We discuss the kinetics of H <inf>2</inf>O and O <inf>2</inf> dissociation on LiH, NaH and KH surfaces.</ce:para>
